Go Big or Go Home: An Analysis of Diet & Fin Effects on Marine Fish Lengths

Haley Weinstein

June 10, 2023

Abstract

A dataset of marine fish attributes includes the diets, caudal fin aspect ratios, and maximum lengths of over 250 different species from the North Atlantic and the North Pacific oceans. Analyzing these characteristics to observe how the physiology of a fish, as well as the diet of a fish, impacts its maximum length can inform future studies of marine fish species. Using an ANOVA test the mean lengths of fish species were compared for different feeding mode groups to see if a particular group was significantly different in length than the others. According to this test, piscivorous (fish-eating) species are longer on average than other species. Correlation and linear regression analyses of maximum lengths against caudal fin aspect ratios reveals that there is a positive correlation between length and fin size.

Introduction

This dataset, compiled by marine biologist Esther Beukhof, is a collection of ecological traits for 6216 different marine fish taxa, including 1702 unique species, 801 genera, and 236 families along with their geographic information. This dataset aims to identify area-specific traits that can account for intraspecific trait variations in fish. Species were identified based off of international scientific bottom-trawl surveys conducted in the Northeast and Northwest Atlantic, as well as the Northeast Pacific (Beukhof). Most trait information was sourced from FishBase, a database of fish species information (Froese), and other values were collected from existing primary literature. For each species, 14 traits were identified, including several different measures of fish-size, trophic levels, lifespans, growth rates, reproductive rates, offspring size, diets, body-shapes, and habitats.
In this analysis, I focused on the maximum length of species as the outcome of interest. The inputs of interest are the species feeding mode and their caudal fin aspect ratio (AR). Feeding mode is the type of food consumed, categorized into different diets including herbivorous, benthivorous, planktivorous, piscivorous, or generalist. The caudal fin aspect ratio (AR) refers to the squared height of the caudal fin divided by the surface area of the caudal fin. This is an important measure because it correlates to swimming speed, activity, metabolism, and food consumption (Beukhof). This data analysis will determine if feeding mode or AR has a significant impact on a fish species length. To simplify this dataset, I will be analyzing 250 randomly selected species of fish and their above traits.
This analysis will provide an ecological and morphological context to fish sizes, which informs future research on marine fish and how their lifestyle and features impacts their physiology. I aim to investigate whether there is difference in marine fish length across different feeding styles, and to investigate if a fishs length can be predicted by its fin aspect ratio.
I hypothesize that the length of marine fish is not equal for different feeding modes. I also hypothesize that caudal fin aspect ratio does not predict the length of a marine fish.

Exploratory Data Analysis

To simplify the data for the purpose of this analysis, I created a new data frame including only the variables of interest. These include the habitat, feeding mode, AR, and max length. I also included the fish species and family as extra relevant information. In this data, the untransformed max lengths were not normally distributed. I discovered this after creating a histogram of the data, which appeared to be skewed right, and a qqPlot, which indicated abnormality. As a final check I conducted a Shapiro-Wilk test, which resulted in a p-value that was less than 0.05, which indicates that I could reject the null hypothesis that the data was normal, and confirm that the untransformed length data was not normal.
I chose to do a log-transformation to make the data normal. I started by creating a new variable which consisted of the log-transformed values of maximum lengths. A histogram of this new log-transformed length variable supported that the transformed data is normal. Similarly, a qqPlot indicated normality of the transformed data. A Shapiro-Wilk test once again led to the rejection of the null hypothesis, which would indicate that the data is not normal. However, the Shapiro- Wilk test is more appropriate for small sample sizes, since larger sample sizes tend to lead to more statistically significant results for this test. Since this dataset has 250 values, I disregarded the results of the Shapiro-Wilk test, and determined that based on a histogram and qqPlot, the log-transformed data is normally distributed, and I can continue to conduct parametric tests on the data (Appendix). Since the sample size is significantly large with 250 samples, I can assume the data to be approximately normal via the Central Limit Theorem.
The first figure illustrates the normality of the log-transformed y-variable (maximum lengths). The first plot is a histogram of the frequency of each log-transformed maximum length. The mean is around 4cm, and the frequency of values on either side of this mean decrease symmetrically on either side. The distribution has a curve that looks like a typical normal distribution. This is a visual indication that this transformed variable is normally distributed. The plot below this histogram is a qqPlot, a diagram which also illustrates normality, as the values in the distribution align with normal values, highlighted in blue (Fig. 1). Normal distribution is a prerequisite requirement for parametric statistical testing, so confirming that this response variable is normally distributed is a key indication that we can proceed with further analysis. The subsequent boxplot sorts the distributions of log-transformed maximum lengths by their respective feeding modes, or diets. This diagram shows the averages, standard deviations, and outliers of log-maximum lengths for each diet group. The piscivorous fish group has the largest average log-maximum length, and the herbivorous group has the lowest. This could indicate that meat-eating fish are generally larger than vegetarian fish, though further statistical analysis will be conducted to confirm or deny this prediction. There are several outliers in the generalist group (Fig. 2). I predict that this is due to the classification of generalist being a broad category, generously including a wide variety of individual diet-types within the broader generalist umbrella. The last figure is a scatterplot which analyzes the relationship between ln-maximum lengths and the caudal fin aspect ratio. The intention of observing this plot is to determine if there is an obvious relationship between these two variables. At a glance, there does not appear to be an obvious relationship, although larger values on one axis seem to correspond with larger values on the other axis (Fig. 3). Further analysis will determine of a statistically significant relationship exists between these two variables.

Statistical Methods

An ANOVA test compares the mean ln-maximum lengths among different feeding mode fish groups to see if at least one group has a significantly different mean length. A post hoc test identifies which feeding mode group is significantly different. A correlation test determines if there is a relationship between caudal fin aspect ratio and maximum length. A linear regression creates the formula describing the relationship that exists between these two variables.

ANOVA: Comparing the mean ln-maximum lengths among fish feeding groups

An ANOVA test is a statistical test used when two or more groups are being compared to each other. Specifically, this test analyzes the variances between groups, and determines if at least one of the means from a group is significantly different from the other groups. The null hypothesis of an ANOVA test is that means of all groups are equal, and the alternative hypothesis of an ANOVA test is that the mean of at least one group is significantly different than the other groups. The p-value of an ANOVA test determines the significance of the test statistic. A significant p-value (less than 0.05) indicates that the null hypothesis can be rejected, and at least one group has a significantly different mean than the other groups. Residuals are the difference between predicted and observed data. The assumptions of this test are that the residuals of the sample are normally distributed, have equal variances, and that the data comes from a random sample.
I will use an ANOVA test to determine whether there is a difference in the mean ln-maximum length of marine fish between each feeding mode. This will reveal if diet has a significant impact on fish length. Before proceeding with an ANOVA test, I checked the tests assumptions. First, I did a visual check of assumptions by graphing the residuals. A graph of the residuals vs fitted has a flat line, which indicates that the homogeneity of variance assumption is met. A qqPlot of residuals showed values following a normal distribution closely, indicating that the assumption of normal distribution was met. A Shapiro Wilk test of normality of residuals resulted in a p value=0.0002586. A p-value < 0.05 for a Shapiro Wilk test indicates rejection of the null hypothesis that the data is normally distributed. Therefore by this test the residuals are not normal. However, when compared with the qqPlot and considering the large sample size (250), the conclusion of the Shapiro Wilk test is not significant. By the Central Limit Theorem, we can conclude that the residuals data is normally distributed because it has a significantly large sample size. The next test conducted to check assumptions was a Levenes test. A Levenes test determines if variances of samples are equal. The null hypothesis of a Levenes test is that the variances of the samples are equal. A Levenes test of ln-maximum lengths vs feeding modes resulted in a p-value=0.06393, which is larger than 0.05 and therefore fails to reject the null hypothesis. Therefore, the variances of the sample groups of feeding modes are equal. Finally, since the fish species data was collected in bottom-trawl surveys of different oceans, the samples are randomly selected. All of the assumptions of an ANOVA test are met, and I can proceed with an ANOVA test.
The null hypothesis of this ANOVA test is that the mean of ln-maximum fish lengths is equal for all feeding modes. The alternative hypothesis is that at least one of the means of ln-maximum fish lengths is different in each of the feeding modes.

H0: The mean ln-fish lengths is equal for all feeding modes. H1: At least one of the means of ln-fish lengths is different in each of the feeding modes.

Following the ANOVA test, the p value=2e-16 was collected, which is less than 0.05. Therefore the null hypothesis is rejected. We can conclude that at least one of the means of ln-fish lengths is different in each of the feeding modes.
To see which group has the most significantly different lengths, I conducted a TukeyHSD post-hoc test, which compares the differences between every group. From this test, I concluded that the piscivorous group has the significantly smallest lengths compared with all other feeding mode groups.

Linear model: Predicting AR from maximum length

To analyze the relationship between maximum length and caudal fin aspect ratio, I first conducted a Pearsons Correlation Test. A Pearsons Correlation Test measures the statistical relationship between two numeric variables. First, I plotted the two variables, ln-maximum length and AR, beside one another to test the assumption of bivariate normality (both variables being normally distributed.) This assumption was not met at first because AR is not normally distributed. I transformed AR using a log-transformation, and the resulting data was normally distributed, as demonstrated by a histogram of the transformed AR variable. I ran the Pearsons Correlation Test on the transformed data and retrieved a correlation value of 0.23167, which suggests a positive correlation between the two variables. A p-value of 0.0002 for this test indicates that we can reject the null hypothesis that there is no significant correlation, and we can conclude that there is a positive correlation between the variables. Next, to create a linear regression model of the relationship between max length and AR, I ran a linear regression and checked assumptions using diagnostic plots. A regression assumes that the sample is random, and that y is normally distributed with equal variance for all values of x. A check of diagnostic plots confirmed that assumptions are met. (Homogeneity of variance is met, as shown by the residuals vs fitted graph). To further confirm that assumptions are met, I conducted a Shapiro Wilk test of the residuals of the linear regression. A p-value of 0.244 on the Shapiro Wilk test means failure to reject the null hypothesis that residuals are normal. Therefore, the residuals are normal. Since assumptions are met, the linear regression model can be constructed. The resulting regression line is ln-maxlength = 3.48002 + 0.24296(AR). With every 1cm increase in the AR of a fish, there is a corresponding 0.24296 increase in the log maximum length of the fish. The multiple r-squared value of 0.05545 means that 5.545% of the variation in ln-maximum lengths (Y) is determined by AR (X).

Fig. 4: These diagnostic plots check to see if the assumptions of a linear regression are met before the analysis can proceed. The residuals vs fitted graph has a flat line, which shows that the assumption of equal variance is met. The qqPlot follows the expected values for a normal distribution, therefore the assumption of noramality of residuals is met.

Results

ANOVA: Comparing the mean ln-maximum lengths among fish feeding groups

The null hypothesis of this ANOVA test is that the mean of ln-maximum fish lengths is equal for all feeding modes. The alternative hypothesis is that at least one of the means of ln-maximum fish lengths is different in each of the feeding modes.
H0: The mean ln-fish lengths is equal for all feeding modes.
H1: At least one of the means of ln-fish lengths is different in each of the feeding modes.
(one-way ANOVA; alpha = 0.05, F-value = 31.99, p-value = 2e-16; Figure ). Following the ANOVA test, the p value=2e-16 was collected, which is less than 0.05. Therefore the null hypothesis that the mean ln-fish lengths is equal for all feeding modes is rejected. We can conclude that at least one of the means of ln-fish lengths is different in each of the feeding modes.
To see which group has significantly different lengths, I conducted a TukeyHSD post-hoc test, which compares the differences between every group. From this test, I concluded that the piscivorous group has significantly large lengths compared with all other feeding mode groups, because compared against every other diet, the piscivorous group strayed from the average the most.

Linear model: Predicting AR from maximum length

I ran the Pearsons Correlation Test on the transformed data and retrieved a correlation value of 0.23167, which suggests a positive correlation between the two variables. A p-value of 0.0002 for this test indicates that we can reject the null hypothesis that there is no significant correlation, and we can conclude that there is a positive correlation between the variables.

Next, I ran the linear regression. (linear regression; alpha = 0.05, F-statistic = 14.56, p-value = 0.0001715, R-squared = 0.05545). The resulting formula is as follows:

ln-maxlength = 3.48002 + 0.24296*(AR).

With every 1cm increase in the AR of a fish, there is a corresponding 0.24296 increase in the log maximum length of the fish. The multiple R-squared value of 0.05545 means that 5.545% of the variation in ln-maximum lengths (Y) is determined by AR (X).

Discussion

The ANOVA test and post hoc test led to the conclusion that the piscivorous feeding mode group has the most significantly large maximum length. A fishs feeding mode does have an impact on the species length. Piscivorous fish being the largest, on average, is a logical finding biologically because a piscivorous diet includes primarily meat, which is high in protein and would make a fish grow larger than a fish that has a planktivorous diet, one consisting of small plankton. My hypothesis that diet affects length was correct. Understanding the implications of diet on physical size can inform future studies on marine fish. If there is little known of a certain marine fish species, analysis of the length of that fish could reveal information about the fishs diet. Or vice versa, if a fish species feeding mode is known, the maximum length of the species could be generally predicted. A limitation of this analysis is that it fails to consider other lifestyle-related factors affecting fish length. For example, the habitat of a fish could have an impact on how its size would affect its survivability. The linear regression analysis of max length vs AR revealed that there is a statistically significant positive correlation between the two variables. The larger the fin aspect ratio, the longer the fish is likely to be. My hypothesis that AR does not correlate to length was incorrect. A fish with a larger fin generally will also have a longer body. The fin aspect ratio has an impact on swimming speed, activity, and metabolism, just as the length will also play an important role in these processes. To further improve this analysis I would include other physiological measurements of the fishs body to analyze other statistical size-related relationships and how they impact the survivability of a fish in its particular ecosystem. The main takeaway of this analysis is that the length of a marine fish is determined by a wide variety of factors, from diet, to fin size. Further studies will determine other factors impacting a fishs length.
